You can edit a Git commit message even after committing,
but the method depends on whether you’ve already pushed it to a remote repository.

If the commit is local (not pushed yet):
Use the --amend option
#git commit --amend

⚠️ If the commit is already pushed:
You can still amend it, but you’ll need to force-push:
#git commit --amend -m "New commit message"
#git push --force
⚠️ Warning: Force-pushing rewrites history, which can cause issues for others working on the same branch.
Only do this if you’re sure it won’t disrupt teammates.

Each commit appears as a single line (short hash + message). Great for quick scanning.
#git log --oneline
#git show <commit-hash>

